<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910411-0022</DOCNO><DOCID>910411-0022.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Unisys Corp.:   Concern Announces Products   Relating to Unix System</HL><DATE>04/11/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C16</SO><CO>   UIS</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)SOFTWARE (SOF)</IN><RE>PENNSYLVANIA (PA)</RE><LP>   Unisys Corp. made a series of announcements introducingcomputer hardware and software products that give it aheadstart of several months on competitors in an importantpart of the Unix market.   Consultants said the Unisys software products make it thefirst to sell an industrial-strength version of a so-calledon-line transaction-processing system that runs on theincreasingly popular Unix operating system. The consultantssay it will be six months to a year before competitors catchup.</LP><TEXT>   Companies have typically used such systems to handle rapidchanges in huge data bases, such as for an airlinereservation system. But as the prices of these systems fall,they are expected to find their way into small businesses.The sorts of technological improvements Unisys announcedyesterday should accelerate the decline in price because Unixsystems, built on industry standards, cost much less thansystems built on manufacturers' proprietary technology.   Unisys, Blue Bell, Pa., said its Open/OLTP software isavailable immediately. The company also announced three U6000 computers that use multiple Intel 386 or 486microprocessors to run the software. The minicomputers,costing between $36,000 and $350,000, will be available inMay.</TEXT></DOC>